## What is Competitive programming (CP)?
**Competitive Programming (CP) **is a mind-sport where you solve challenging logic and math-based problems using code â€” usually under a limited time (1â€“5 hours).
Think of it as a **coding Olympics **, where instead of athletic strength, you use **your brain, algorithms, and speed.**
That is why it is also known as** Sport Programming or Speed Programming**
#### What kind of problems do you solve?
Examples:
- â€œGiven a big number, check if it is *prime* or notâ€
- â€œFind the **shortest path** between two cities on a map.â€
- â€œGiven N students and friendships, count the number of **friend groups**.â€
These require:
- Logical thinking
- Mathematical patterns
- Algorithmic tricks
- Clean and fast code
This is NOT making apps or websites â€” itâ€™s **pure problem solving and algorithms**.
You donâ€™t give answers to the question, instead you write programs that can.
#### Why do people do Competitive Programming?
- It enhances your **problem-solving abilities and mental agility**
- It provides the satisfaction and engagement of solving challenging puzzles
- You can participate in online competitions and improve your **ratings & rankings**
- Top competitors gain access to career opportunities, recognition, and valuable internships
- It serves as the primary pathway to qualify for **IOI** and later **ICPC (university level)** competitions
**Check out this Video**
**Competitive Programming: Explained by an IOI medalist**

## Pakistan IOI team Selection Process
The journey to represent Pakistan at the [International Olympiad in Informatics (IOI)](https://ioinformatics.org/)[ ](https://ioinformatics.org/)starts with the [Pakistan Olympiad in Informatics (POI)](https://www.fbise.edu.pk/IOI.php)[ ](https://www.fbise.edu.pk/IOI.php)â€” a multi-round national selection pipeline organized by the **Federal Board of Intermediate & Secondary Education (FBISE)**.
#### ðŸ”¹ **Round 1 â€“ Online Qualifier**
- Registrations usually open **around Novemberâ€“December**.
- The test is typically an **online**[ Codeforces](http://codeforces.com)** contest**, but students must appear **physically** at official test centers set up in **major cities across Pakistan**.
- Around **50â€“70 top scorers** are shortlisted from all over the country.
#### ðŸ”¹ **Round 2 â€“ Advanced Problem-Solving**
- Shortlisted students are invited for a **higher-level coding test**, again supervised at physical centers.
- Problems are more algorithmic and closer to IOI style.
- The list is narrowed down further to select the **top ~15â€“20 students**.
- **Important Point:** They may just have one round and in that case around 25-30 students will be shortlisted directly for Round 1 for Final Round.
#### ðŸ”¹ **Round 3 â€“ Final Round**
- All those students will get to participate in Asia Pacific Olympiad in Informatics APIO (Highly Prestigious Competition).
- Final Round will be an IOI-style Contest.
- Most Probably, Final Team Selection Test of some other country or APIO.
- Top 4 scorers in the Final Round will make it to Pakistan IOI team.
#### ðŸ **International Representation**
- The selected team represents ðŸ‡µðŸ‡° at the **IOI**, hosted each year by a different country.
- [IOI 2026](https://ioi2026.uz/), Tashkent, Uzbekistan.  August 9-16
- IOI 2027, Potsdam, Germany. September 12-19
- IOI 2028,  Japan
- IOI 2029, Bulgaria

## Start from Zero (Step-by-Step)
## How to Start [Competitive Programming](/2455dbb3971780f38f0dc9f9ad5321f5?pvs=25)?
### Step 0: Find Your *Why*
- **Before coding, know your purpose.** Ask: *â€œWhy do I want to learn programming?â€*
- Possible strong reasons:
- I want to represent Pakistan at [IOI](http://ioinformatics.org)[ ](/2455dbb3971780fd94abdd7bb4b11738?pvs=25)**or **[ICPC](https://icpc.global/)
- I want a **scholarship** to a top university (MIT, KAIST, etc.)
- I love solving **logic puzzles** and coding challenges
- I want to build my future through **tech & problem-solving**
- **Programming is hard.** Youâ€™ll feel stuck, confused, and frustrated â€” thatâ€™s normal.
- What matters is **grit**, not genius. Start with a strong reason, and donâ€™t stop.
- **Write your goal** somewhere visible. Look at it when you feel like quitting.
> â€œWeak purpose dies at the first bug. Strong purpose turns bugs into fuel.â€
### Step 1: Required Hardware & Software
#### ðŸ–¥ï¸ Hardware (Minimum)
- âœ… **Laptop/Desktop** (recommended)
- Internet
#### ðŸ’½ Software (for C++ Programming)
- Linux operating System is recommended but you can use windows or MacOS
- Code Editor: Sublime Text/ VS code/ VIM/ etc
- **MinGW / g++** (C++ compiler)
- **Terminal / CMD / PowerShell** (to run code)
- Optional: Use OnlineGDB or Replit for browser-based coding
### ðŸ‘¨â€ðŸ’» Step 2: Learn C++ Basics
Why C++? Only C++ is allowed in IOI, It is almost 30 times Faster than python in run-times and more than 90% Competitive programmers use C++ (means more content available in C++).
#### What You Need to Learn First
Start with the **fundamentals** â€” donâ€™t jump straight into algorithms or Advanced Data structures.
- **Basic Syntax** (how C++ code is written)
- **Variables & Data Types** (int, char, string, etc.)
- **Input & Output** (cin, cout)
- **Loops** (for, while)
- **If-else** (conditions)
- **Functions**
- **Arrays**
- **Practice using simple math problems **on codeforces, atcoder
- [w3schools website](https://www.w3schools.com/cpp/) and [Apna college Playlist](https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLfqMhTWNBTe0b2nM6JHVCnAkhQRGiZMSJ) can be used to learn Basic C++.
### Step 3: Start Solving Problems
- C++ is useless without **problem solving**
To get good at IOI-level problem solving, you must train on **real platforms like Codeforces** and **build your thinking muscle** through hard practice â€” not shortcuts.
#### Join Codeforces
- [Register Here](http://codeforces.com)
- Explore the **Problemset**
- Start solving **800 rating** problems
- Focus on topics like:
- Input/Output
- Loops & If-Else
- Arrays & Strings
- Basic math problems
#### Participate in Contests
- Codeforces hosts **rated contests every week**
- Join these contests **LIVE** â€” youâ€™ll learn how to:
- Think under pressure
- Manage time
- Handle bugs & edge cases
- Donâ€™t wait until you''re â€œreadyâ€ â€” **start early**
- By Codeforces Rating, you will know you current level and recent progress
- So contests are not test but a personal assesment.
#### ðŸ›‘ Donâ€™t Use AI or Google to Solve
- âŒ Donâ€™t copy/paste solutions from YouTube, ChatGPT, or blogs
- âŒ Donâ€™t ask AI to debug your contest code
- âœ… **Struggle, fail, and retry, thatâ€™s how your brain grows**
- Using AI during contests kills your growth, itâ€™s like Using Car to practice for Running.
- Codeforces is an international Platform, Cheating there is dishonesty and Insult of your Country.
> If you don''t struggle, you don''t improve.
### Resources:
- [usaco.guide](http://usaco.guide) Amazing Guide for CP and Full of Resources
- [Codeforces](http://codeforces.com) and [Atcoder](http://atcoder.jp) Best website for Competitive Programming and Live Contest.
- Youtube Channel: [Algorithms with Shayan](https://www.youtube.com/@AlgorithmswithShayan)
#### What to Avoid Early On
- âŒ Blindly watching tutorials without solving problems
- âŒ Using ChatGPT/YouTube for every stuck problem
- âŒ Jumping to hard problems too early (demotivating)

